---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import { SITE_URL, breadcrumbList } from '../../lib/schema';

const url = `${SITE_URL}/quickstart/`;
const title = 'Quickstart — Runlog';
const description =
  'Set up Runlog with Claude Code (or any MCP-capable agent) in four steps: register, wire MCP, drop in the client skill, use Claude normally.';

const graph = [
  breadcrumbList([
    { name: 'Runlog', url: `${SITE_URL}/` },
    { name: 'Quickstart', url },
  ]),
  {
    '@type': 'HowTo',
    '@id': `${url}#howto`,
    name: 'Quickstart — Set up Runlog',
    description,
    url,
    inLanguage: 'en',
    datePublished: '2026-05-03',
    author: { '@id': `${SITE_URL}/#organization` },
    publisher: { '@id': `${SITE_URL}/#organization` },
    isPartOf: { '@id': `${SITE_URL}/#website` },
    step: [
      { '@type': 'HowToStep', position: 1, name: 'Register and grab a key', text: 'Register an email, click the verification link, and copy the API key.' },
      { '@type': 'HowToStep', position: 2, name: 'Wire the MCP server into Claude Code', text: 'Run npx add-mcp https://api.runlog.org/mcp -a claude-code or hand-edit ~/.claude/settings.json.' },
      { '@type': 'HowToStep', position: 3, name: 'Drop in the client skill', text: 'Copy skills/claude-code/SKILL.md into ~/.claude/skills/runlog/SKILL.md to teach Claude the four-point contract.' },
      { '@type': 'HowToStep', position: 4, name: 'Use Claude normally', text: 'Describe the problem; Claude decides when to query Runlog automatically.' },
    ],
  },
];
---
<Base
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonical={url}
  ogType="article"
  ogDescription={description}
  twitterDescription={description}
  graph={graph}
>
  <p slot="crumbs" class="crumbs"><a href="/">&larr; Runlog</a></p>

  <section aria-labelledby="hero-title" class="prose">
    <h1 id="hero-title">Quickstart</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Set up Runlog with Claude Code in four steps: register, wire MCP, drop in the
      client skill, use Claude normally. The same shape works for every supported
      adapter &mdash; see <a href="/agents/">Agents</a> for vendor-specific paths.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="setup-title" class="prose">
    <h2 id="setup-title">Set it up</h2>
    <p>
      Runlog is consumed through an MCP server plus a small client skill. You don't call it
      yourself &mdash; your agent does, automatically, only when the problem is about a third-party
      system your team memory hasn't covered yet. The setup is the same shape across every
      supported agent: register, wire MCP, drop in the skill, then your agent decides when to
      query. Steps below show <strong>Claude Code</strong> as the example; the
      <a href="/agents/">other adapters</a> follow the same shape with vendor-specific
      config paths.
    </p>

    <h3 id="step-1">1. Register and grab a key</h3>
    <p>
      <a href="/register/">Register an email</a>, click the verification link, and copy the
      key (shown once, format <code>sk-runlog-&lt;id&gt;-&lt;secret&gt;</code>). Store it in
      your password manager. Export it: <code>export RUNLOG_API_KEY="sk-runlog-&hellip;"</code>.
    </p>

    <h3 id="step-2">2. Wire the MCP server into Claude Code</h3>
    <p>
      Fastest path &mdash; Neon's
      <a href="https://github.com/neondatabase/add-mcp"><code>add-mcp</code></a>
      reads Runlog's <a href="https://registry.modelcontextprotocol.io/">Official MCP Registry</a>
      entry and writes the right config for you:
    </p>
<pre><code>npx add-mcp https://api.runlog.org/mcp -a claude-code</code></pre>
    <div class="callout" data-tag="HOST KEY">
      <code>add-mcp</code> uses <code>claude-code</code> as the host key; the runlog-installer uses <code>claude</code> (matches <code>runlog install --target claude</code>). Both target the same host with different naming conventions, pick whichever installer suits your workflow.
    </div>
    <p>
      Or, if you'd rather edit by hand, add to <code>~/.claude/settings.json</code>:
    </p>
<pre><code>{`{
  "mcpServers": {
    "runlog": {
      "type": "http",
      "url": "https://api.runlog.org/mcp",
      "headers": { "Authorization": "Bearer \${RUNLOG_API_KEY}" }
    }
  }
}`}</code></pre>
    <p>Confirm with <code>claude mcp list</code> &mdash; <code>runlog</code> should show as connected.
    <code>add-mcp</code> also covers Cursor and Cline; for Continue, Windsurf, and other
    vendors see the <a href="/agents/">per-adapter cards</a>.</p>

    <h3 id="step-3">3. Drop in the client skill</h3>
    <p>
      Copy <a href="https://github.com/runlog-org/runlog-skills/blob/main/claude-code/SKILL.md"><code>skills/claude-code/SKILL.md</code></a>
      into <code>~/.claude/skills/runlog/SKILL.md</code>. The skill teaches Claude four rules:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>Check team memory (<code>CLAUDE.md</code>, Cursor rules, conversation context) <em>before</em> calling Runlog.</li>
      <li>Only call <code>runlog_search</code> when the problem is classified as an external-dependency problem.</li>
      <li>Route new learnings to the right layer &mdash; internal patterns into team memory, third-party-system findings into <code>runlog_submit</code>.</li>
      <li>Track which entries were applied in a session manifest, then call <code>runlog_report</code> with the outcome.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Without the skill, Runlog is just three MCP tools &mdash; Claude won't know when to use them.
      With the skill, the workflow is automatic.
    </p>

    <h3 id="step-4">4. Use Claude normally</h3>
    <p>
      You don't type "search Runlog" &mdash; that's the wrong layer. You describe the problem and
      Claude decides. Example prompts that will route through Runlog:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>"Stripe webhook signature keeps failing intermittently in production &mdash; figure out why."</li>
      <li>"This Shopware 6 variant import dies past 500 rows. Fix it."</li>
      <li>"OAuth redirect on Google Workspace returns <code>invalid_grant</code> half the time."</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Claude checks team memory first. If your <code>CLAUDE.md</code> already documents the
      fix, Runlog is never queried. If it doesn't and the problem is about a third-party
      system, Claude calls <code>runlog_search</code>, applies whatever it finds, then
      reports the outcome back so the trust score updates. If Claude solves the problem
      independently and the learning is generic, the skill prompts it to submit the finding.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
